@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

<> a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "RDF Document Authoring — Document Entity, No Blank Nodes, schema:author, and Terminology"@en ;
    schema:description "Foundational rules for self-describing RDF Turtle documents: document entity declaration, no blank nodes, schema:author over foaf:maker, and Semantic Web terminology."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-05T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-25T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:author <https://linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this> ;
    schema:about :step-documentEntity, :step-documentAbout, :step-noBlankNodes-detail,
        :step-schemaAuthorOverFoafMaker-detail, :step-terminologySemanticWeb-detail ;
    schema:step :step-documentEntity, :step-documentAbout, :step-noBlankNodes-detail,
        :step-schemaAuthorOverFoafMaker-detail, :step-terminologySemanticWeb-detail ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <../preferences.ttl#step-documentEntity>, <../preferences.ttl#step-documentAbout>, <../preferences.ttl#step-noBlankNodes>, <../preferences.ttl#step-schemaAuthorOverFoafMaker>, <../preferences.ttl#step-terminologySemanticWeb> .

# ── Step 1: Document Entity Declaration ──────────────────────────────────────

:step-documentEntity a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "1"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Declare the document entity in every TTL file using <>"@en ;
    schema:text "Every Turtle document MUST declare its own container entity using the empty IRI reference <>, which denotes the document itself (its retrieval URL). Do NOT use : (which is shorthand for <#>, a hash fragment within the document — a local named entity, not the document). The correct pattern is: '<> a schema:CreativeWork ; schema:name {title} ; schema:description {summary} ; schema:dateModified {now()} ; schema:author {authorIRI} ; schema:about {primaryTopic} .' This applies universally to all system-related Turtle documents: preferences.ttl, core.ttl, index.ttl, ontology.ttl, all session files, project files, and entity files. Using <> makes the document a self-describing, dereferenceable resource whose identity is its retrieval address, enabling schema:about to correctly express what the document is about. Timestamps MUST use the current time (now()) in ISO 8601 UTC format (e.g., \"2026-05-29T21:22:00Z\"^^xsd:dateTime). For new files, set both schema:dateCreated and schema:dateModified to now(). For updates to existing files, update only schema:dateModified."@en .

# ── Step 2: Document Entity schema:about ────────────────────────────────────

:step-documentAbout a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "2"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Use schema:about for the document entity"@en ;
    schema:text "The document-level CreativeWork MUST use schema:about to link to its primary topic, NOT schema:mainEntity. schema:about is the correct predicate for describing what a CreativeWork is about. schema:mainEntity is reserved for specific use cases such as schema:FAQPage mainEntity linking. When in doubt, use schema:about for the document container entity."@en .

# ── Step 3: No Blank Nodes in RDF Output ─────────────────────────────────────

:step-noBlankNodes-detail a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "3"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Never use blank nodes in generated RDF Turtle — all resources must be named IRIs"@en ;
    schema:text """Every resource in generated RDF MUST be a named IRI. Blank nodes are prohibited in all forms.

Prohibited patterns:
1. Turtle [ ... ] inline blank node syntax — e.g., :x :p [ a :Class ; :q "v" ] is prohibited.
2. Turtle _:id blank node labels — e.g., _:b1 a :Class is prohibited.
3. Turtle ( ... ) collection syntax — e.g., :x :p (:a :b) desugars to blank node list cells; use comma-separated objects instead: :x :p :a, :b.
4. Any other blank node construct (e.g., rdf:first/rdf:rest chains from collections).

Always use comma-separated object lists for multiple values:
- Correct: :glossarySection schema:hasDefinedTerm :term1, :term2, :term3 .
- Wrong: :glossarySection schema:hasDefinedTerm (:term1 :term2 :term3) .

Verification gate (run after every RDF generation):
grep -cE '\\[|\\(:|_: ' {ttl-file}
If the count is > 0, fix all blank nodes before delivering the RDF.

Why: Named IRIs are queryable, referencable, and resolvable. Blank nodes cannot be addressed from outside the file, cannot be resolved via content negotiation, and break the hyperlinked-data model that is the foundation of the Semantic Web."""@en .

# ── Step 4: schema:author over foaf:maker ─────────────────────────────────────

:step-schemaAuthorOverFoafMaker-detail a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "4"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Use schema:author instead of foaf:maker — always"@en ;
    schema:text """When attributing document authorship in any RDF serialization or embedded JSON-LD, use schema:author. Never use foaf:maker.

In Turtle (.ttl):
  schema:author <https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this> ;

In JSON-LD (@context uses @vocab: http://schema.org/):
  "author": { "@type": "Person", "@id": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this", "name": "Kingsley Uyi Idehen" }

What NOT to do:
  - Never add foaf:maker to any document entity
  - Never add "foaf": "http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/" to @context solely to support foaf:maker
  - Do not use foaf:maker as a "WebID-native" complement to schema:author — schema:author already carries that role

Applies to:
  - <> (self-describing CreativeWork) in all .ttl session, howto, and project files
  - script type=application/ld+json blocks in HTML infographics
  - Any WebPage, CreativeWork, or Dataset entity in generated RDF

Why: The user confirmed schema:author is the sole authorship term. foaf:maker adds no value that schema:author does not already cover and introduces an unnecessary vocabulary dependency."""@en .

# ── Step 5: Semantic Web Terminology ─────────────────────────────────────────

:step-terminologySemanticWeb-detail a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "5"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Terminology: 'the Semantic Web' is unacceptable — always 'a Semantic Web' or 'purpose-specific Semantic Webs'"@en ;
    schema:text """TIGHTENED 2026-07-18: the definite-article phrase "the Semantic Web" is unacceptable in all contexts, including references to the global vision. Always use one of:

- "a Semantic Web" (indefinite, singular) — a specific deployment of machine-computable entity relationships constructed using Linked Data principles.
- "purpose-specific Semantic Webs" (plural) — the general phenomenon of many such deployments, each webby and dereferenceable, none canonical or singular.

There is no single "the Semantic Web" to refer to — even the original W3C vision is, in this framing, one purpose-specific Semantic Web among many, not a definite, singular, already-realized thing. This supersedes the prior wording of this rule, which permitted "the Semantic Web" when referring to the global Web-wide vision; that exception no longer applies. Caught during the loops-to-graphs-semantic-web-context-claude_code-1 meshup (2026-07-18), where "the Semantic Web vision" and "what the Semantic Web does not supply" both had to be rewritten.

This distinction mirrors the analogous Web/web distinction:
- the Web = the global World Wide Web.
- a web = a specific interconnected network (e.g., a web of trust, an intranet web, a domain-specific web).

Enforcement: In all generated content (HTML infographics, RDF descriptions, FAQ answers, glossary definitions, Markdown companions, etc.), use "a Semantic Web" (or "A Semantic Web" at sentence start) when the reference is to an instance, deployment, or specific stack. Use "the Semantic Web" only when explicitly referring to the global Web-wide vision/ecosystem.

This also applies to derived phrases: "the Semantic Web stack" should become "a Semantic Web stack", "the Semantic Web context" should become "a Semantic Web context", etc."""@en .
